    <title>Combined summary - CLTV/CSV/etc. deployment considerations due to XT/Not-BitcoinXT miners</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T20:33:34.827586+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010410.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email conversation on the bitcoin-dev mailing list primarily revolves around the implementation of nVersion mask and IsSuperMajority() in the Bitcoin protocol. There are three proposed deployment options for CSV, CLTV, and other soft-forks, with the second option of using nVersion mask with IsSuperMajority() being favored. This option involves masking away nVersion bits set by XT/Not-Bitcoin-XT miners before applying standard IsSuperMajority() logic. The deployment of these soft-forks has been complicated by the existence of XT and Not-Bitcoin-XT miners who produce blocks with nVersion=0x20000007, which triggers false implementations using the IsSuperMajority() mechanism and nVersion=4 blocks.Another proposal suggests using a specific version-bits proposal to handle upgrades, which involves reserving bits for feature upgrade forks, agreeing on a specific standard, and implementing it in a time window. However, this proposal is still under review and yet to be implemented.In August 2015, developer Peter Todd proposed the implementation of a nVersion mask for IsSuperMajority(), which would allow miners running Bitcoin Core to create blocks with the nVersion set to 8. The proposal also suggested that, for the purpose of soft-fork warnings, the highest known version can remain nVersion=8, which is triggered by both XT/Not-Bitcoin-XT blocks as well as a future nVersion bits implementation. The proposal states that further IsSuperMajority() soft forks can be accomplished with the same masking technique. Jorge Timón expressed interest in helping with the implementation of versionbits, stating it as the "most future-proof" solution. However, versionbits has not been implemented yet, and the BIP is still under review. In the absence of versionbits, another IsSuperMajority() rollout has been indicated by Pieter, to be used as a deployment method until versionbits is ready.There are concerns raised about conflicting upgrades and the need to reject blocks with versions lower than 8 if the new upgrade is accepted by a majority of nodes. To address these concerns, a possible solution was proposed that would involve setting N (the height at which the rule is active) one year from now or so, and giving a period of time after lock that bit 8 will be kept and another period where it is guaranteed to be zero. This would allow software that is only watching the bit time to be upgraded and a similar amount of time where the bit is set to zero before it can be reused.Overall, the email conversation on the bitcoin-dev mailing list covered various proposals and concerns related to version bits for BIP 65, 68, and other upgrades. These discussions aimed to find solutions to issues raised by Bitcoin XT and ensure forward compatibility with future soft forks while maintaining consensus rules.</summary>
